<section xml:id="activity-combinations-of-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Combinations of Functions</title>

    <p>There are many ways and reasons to combine two or more functions together. In the first exercise, you will combine two functions in the context of performing a familiar activity: paying bills</p>
    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <setup>
          <var name="$heat"><static>95</static></var>
          <var name="$water"><static>35</static></var>
          <var name="$billNumber"><static>130</static></var>
          <var name="$billExpression">
            <set>
              <member>\text{?}</member>
              <member>H(x)</member>
              <member>W(x)</member>
              <member>H(x) \cdot W(x)</member>
              <member correct="yes">H(x)+W(x)</member>
            </set>
          </var>
          <pg-code>
            $heat=random(80,120,5);
            $water=random(20,50,5);
            $billNumber=$heat+$water;
            parserFunction("h(x)"=>"(sin(x)+2)/pi");
            parserFunction("w(x)"=>"(cos(5*x)+6)/pi");
            Context()->flags->set(reduceConstantFunctions=>0);
            Context()->flags->set(formatStudentAnswer=>"parsed");
            parserFunction("f(x)"=>"(sin(x)+2)/pi");
            $billExpression=Formula("h(x)+w(x)");
          </pg-code>
        </setup>
        <statement>
          <p>Suppose you are only responsible to pay the heating and water bills each month. These bills change each month, depending on how warm you keep your house and on how much water you use.</p>
          <p>Let <m>h(x)</m> represent the heating bill (in dollars) for month <m>x</m>, and let <m>w(x)</m> represent the water bill (in dollars) for month <m>x</m>.</p>
          <p>Let <m>x = 2</m> represent February, which is the <m>2^{\rm{nd}}</m> month of the year. Also, suppose <m>h(2) = <var name="$heat" /></m> and <m>w(2) = <var name="$water" /></m>.</p>
          <p>Now, let <m>b(x)</m> represent the total amount you must pay in bills for month <m>x</m>. What is <m>b(2)</m>?</p>
          <p>Answer:  <var name="$billNumber" width="10" /> dollars</p>
          <p>For any month <m>x</m>, what is <m>b(x)</m>?</p>
          <p>Answer:  <var name="$billExpression" form="popup" /></p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <p>If you need to add two functions together, such as <m>f(x)+g(x)</m>, this represents a <term>combination of functions</term><index><main>combination of functions</main></index><index><main>function</main><sub>combinations</sub></index>. Sometimes, you will see the combination <m>f(x)+g(x)</m> written as: <me>\left(f+g\right)(x)</me></p>
    <p>This means that <m>f+g</m> is a new function of <m>x</m>, whose output is just the sum of the outputs of the functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.</p>
    <p>Of course, there are other ways to combine the outputs of two or more functions.</p>

  <exercise>
    <webwork xml:id="combinations-first-example">

      <setup>
        <var name="$x"><static>7</static></var>
        <var name="$M"><static>3</static></var>
        <var name="$N"><static>4</static></var>
        <var name="$s"><static>7</static></var>
        <var name="$d"><static>-1</static></var>
        <var name="$p"><static>16</static></var>
        <var name="$q"><static>4</static></var>

        <pg-code>
          $x=random(2,4,1);
          $M=random(5,8,1);
          $N=random(9,12,1);
          $s=$M+$N;
          $d=$M-$N;
          $p=$M*$N;
          $q=$M/$N;
        </pg-code>

      </setup>
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose we have the following facts about functions <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>:</p>
        <p><md><mrow>M(<var name="$x" />) \amp= <var name="$M" /></mrow><mrow>N(<var name="$x" />) \amp= <var name="$N" /></mrow></md></p>
        <p>If we define a new function <me>s(x) = M(x) + N(x)</me> then we could evaluate <m>s(<var name="$x" />)</m> by merely adding <m>M(<var name="$x" />)</m> and <m>N(<var name="$x" />)</m>.</p>
        <p>Answer: <m>s(<var name="$x" />)</m> = <var name="$s" width="10" /></p>
        <p>Now, we could define many other functions which are combinations of <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>, such as:</p>
        <p><md><mrow>d(x) \amp= M(x) - N(x)</mrow><mrow>p(x) \amp= M(x)*N(x)</mrow><mrow>q(x) \amp= \frac{\displaystyle{M(x)}}{\displaystyle{N(x)}}</mrow></md></p>
        <p>Using these definitions, evaluate each of the following:</p>
        <p><ul>
          <li><p><m>d(</m><var name="$x" /><m>) = </m><var name="$d" width="10" /></p></li>
          <li><p><m>p(</m><var name="$x" /><m>) = </m><var name="$p" width="10" /></p></li>
          <li><p><m>q(</m><var name="$x" /><m>) = </m><var name="$q" width="10" /></p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><ul>
          <li><p><m>s(<var name="$x" />) = </m><var name="$s" /></p></li>
          <li><p><m>d(</m><var name="$x" /><m>) = </m><var name="$d" /></p></li>
          <li><p><m>p(</m><var name="$x" /><m>) = </m><var name="$p" /></p></li>
          <li><p><m>q(</m><var name="$x" /><m>) = </m><var name="$q" /></p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </solution>
    </webwork>
  </exercise>
  <p>Again, combining functions just means <q>doing arithmetic</q> on the outputs of functions. The next exercise gives you information about two functions, and you must use them to compute values for different function combinations.</p>

